.Im MicroEmacs macro;function;miscellaneous|bind
.so me.tni
.TH &cbind 4
.XI &cbind - "Return the command a key is bound to"
.XI &nbind - "Return the numerial argument of a binding"
.XI &kbind - "Return the key a command is bound to"
.SH NAME
&cbind, &kbind, &nkind \- Command/key binding operators
.SH SYNOPSIS
.na
.B &cbind
.I key
.br
.B &nbind
.I key
.br
.B &kbind
.I n
.I command
.ad
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fB&cbind\fR returns the command bound to the given key sequence, \fB&cbind\fR can be abbreviated to \fB&cbi\fR. If
the key is not bound then \fB&cbind\fR returns the string "\fIERROR\fR".
.PP
\fB&nbind\fR returns the numerical argument associated with the given key binding, \fB&nbind\fR can be abbreviated to
\fB&nbi\fR. If the key is not bound then \fB&nbind\fR returns the string "\fIERROR\fR", if the binding has no argument
then an empty string (\fC""\fR) is returned.
.PP
\fB&kbind\fR returns a key sequence bound to the given \fIcommand\fR with the given numerical argument \fIn\fR, use an
empty string (\fC""\fR) for no argument. If no binding can be found then \fB&kbind\fR returns an empty string
(\fC""\fR).
.SH EXAMPLE
The  following  example  waits for the user to press a key, then  prints  what
command the key is bound to.
.Me $emf-scheme
.CS
ml-write "Enter key: "
set-variable #l0 @cgk
ml-write &spr "%s is bound to %s" #l0 &cbin #l0
.CE 0
.Me $ehf-scheme
.SH NOTES
In March 2001 \fB&kbind\fR was renamed \fB&ckind\fR and a new \fB&nkind\fR and
\fB&kbind\fR added.
